@felipe_artur mentioned in https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/issues/329435#note_1165768324:

> Requirements IIDs are also still used on GraphQL API endpoints for filtering, but these are also going to be deprecated.

Before we can proceed with requirements API deprecation in #329432, we'll need to support work item IID for filtering as well as requirement IID to support customers moving across to use the work item IID.

- Modify the finder
- Add an argument for `work_item_iid` or similar in the GraphQL resolver
- Handle if the work item isn't a Requirement or if the Requirement isn't in the project, etc

The following query should work:

```graphql
query {
  project(fullPath: "gitlab-org/gitlab") {
    requirements(work_item_iids: [1, 2]) {
      nodes {
        title
        iid
        work_item_iid
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Contribution analytics currently renders two separate Vue apps. Ideally we should merge the Group Member Contributions table into the same app so it can benefit from a shared hierarchy.

Suggested change:
```diff
import initContributionAnalytics from 'ee/analytics/contribution_analytics';
-import initGroupMemberContributions from 'ee/group_member_contributions';

const el = document.getElementById('js-contribution-analytics');
if (el) {
  initContributionAnalytics(el);
-  initGroupMemberContributions();
}
```
https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/blob/master/ee/app/assets/javascripts/pages/groups/contribution_analytics/show/index.js

## Proposal

As part of https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/merge_requests/100714+ it was determined that the [Cube JS library](https://github.com/cube-js/cube.js/blob/09ceffbefc75417555f8ff90f6277bd9c419d751/packages/cubejs-client-core/src/index.js#L50) doesn't support sending `POST` requests within the GitLab environment. When POST requests are sent, the pages existing headers (authorizations etc) are not sent with the request, whilst when GET requests are sent, the pages existing headers are sent.

## Possible solution

Create an Upstream PR to get the headers of the existing page attached to all POST requests sent.

## Final solution

It turns out that this is possible using a custom `HttpTransport` combined with the same steps we use for `axios` requests:

```js
import { CubejsApi, HttpTransport } from '@cubejs-client/core';
import csrf from '~/lib/utils/csrf';

const cubejsApi = new CubejsApi('1', {
  transport: new HttpTransport({
    apiUrl: '/api/v4/projects/1/product_analytics/request',
    method: 'POST',
    headers: {
      [csrf.headerKey]: csrf.token,
      'X-Requested-With': 'XMLHttpRequest',
    },
    credentials: 'same-origin',
  }),
});
```

So this will be used and some changes made in https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/merge_requests/100714+ will be reverted.
